Variable Size Sliding Window
Deep Dive — when k is not given and the window grows and shrinks by condition

The Thought Pattern (Before Writing Anything)
Ask yourself these 3 questions when you see a variable window problem:

1
What is my window valid condition?
→ when do I keep expanding? e.g. "no duplicates", "sum ≤ k", "all same char"
2
What triggers shrinking?
→ the moment the condition breaks, move left pointer to fix it
3
What do I record per valid window?
→ its length? its start index? a count?
Core insight — right pointer always moves forward one step at a time. Left pointer only moves when the window becomes invalid. You never reset both pointers.

The Mental Model
Two pointers, left and right, both start at 0. right expands the window; left shrinks it from the left when needed.

arr = [a, b, c, d, e, f]

right expands →  →  →  →  →  →
left only moves when condition breaks ↑

The window at any moment = arr[left .. right]
window size = right - left + 1
The Generic Pseudocode
VARIABLE SLIDING WINDOW TEMPLATE

1. left = 0, right = 0
   initialise your tracking structure
   (a sum, a HashMap, a Set, a counter)

2. Loop: right goes from 0 to arr.length - 1

   a. ADD arr[right] into your window state

   b. WHILE window is INVALID (condition broken):
        REMOVE arr[left] from your window state
        left++

   c. At this point window is valid.
      RECORD your answer:
        → length = right - left + 1
        → or update maxLen, count, etc.

3. Return answer
The while vs if choice: use while when the window might need multiple left shrinks to become valid again. Use if only when one shrink is always enough (rare).

The Thought Steps Mapped Out
STEP 1 — right enters and adds to window state

STEP 2 — check condition
   ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
   │  if window VALID                             │
   │    → record result (max length, count, etc.) │
   │                                              │
   │  if window INVALID                           │
   │    → remove arr[left] from state             │
   │    → left++                                  │
   │    → repeat until valid again                │
   └──────────────────────────────────────────────┘

STEP 3 — right++ (loop handles this)

STEP 4 — return answer
Concrete Example — Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
Input: s = "abcabcbb"   Output: 3 (window "abc")

Trace
left=0, right=0, set={}, maxLen=0

right=0 → add 'a' → set={a} → valid → maxLen=max(0,1)=1
right=1 → add 'b' → set={a,b} → valid → maxLen=2
right=2 → add 'c' → set={a,b,c} → valid → maxLen=3
right=3 → add 'a' → INVALID (a already in set)
→ remove arr[left=0]='a', left=1 → set={b,c,a} → valid → maxLen=3
right=4 → add 'b' → INVALID
→ remove arr[left=1]='b', left=2 → valid → maxLen=3
right=5 → add 'c' → INVALID
→ remove arr[left=2]='c', left=3 → valid → maxLen=3
right=6 → add 'b' → INVALID
→ remove arr[left=3]='a', left=4
→ still invalid (b in set) → remove 'b', left=5 → valid → maxLen=3
right=7 → add 'b' → INVALID → shrink → maxLen stays 3

return 3 ✅
What Changes Per Problem — The Only Variable Part
Problem type	Condition for validity	What you track
No repeating chars	all chars unique	HashSet of chars
Max sum ≤ target	windowSum ≤ k	running integer sum
At most k distinct chars	map.size() ≤ k	HashMap of char frequencies
Longest subarray of 1s (can flip k 0s)	zeroCount ≤ k	integer counter of zeros in window
Min window substring	all required chars covered	two frequency maps + formed counter
The Two Rules to Never Forget
Rule 1 — right never goes backwards. It only moves forward. If you find yourself resetting right, you've broken the pattern.

Rule 2 — When you move left, you must undo the contribution of arr[left] from your state first, then increment. Order matters: remove → left++, never left++ → remove.

Fixed vs Variable — Quick Comparison
Fixed window	Variable window
Window size	k is given, constant	not given, changes
Right pointer	always moves by 1	always moves by 1
Left pointer	always moves by 1 (i−k)	moves only when invalid
Shrink trigger	window full (exactly k)	condition breaks
Key structure	sum / freq array	HashSet / HashMap / counter
Signal phrase	"every subarray of size k"	"longest / shortest subarray where…"
Your Practice Checklist for This Pattern
○
Longest substring without repeating chars ← start here, uses a Set
○
Longest subarray with sum ≤ k ← uses integer sum
○
Longest substring with at most k distinct chars ← uses HashMap
○
Max consecutive 1s III (flip k zeros) ← uses zero counter
○
Minimum window substring ← hardest, uses two maps + formed counter
Once you can do all five from memory, variable window is locked in.